ionship with nêhiyawêwin, the Cree language, and the ways in which it informs her relationships and poetics. The introduction by David Gaertner situates Halfe’s writing within the history of whiteness and colonialism that works to silence and repress Indigenous voices. Gaertner pays particular attention to the ways in which Halfe addresses, incorporates, and pushes back against silence, and suggests that her work is an act of bearing witness – what Kwagiulth scholar Sarah Hunt identifies as making Indigenous lives visible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree IndiansvPoetry. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aPoetry. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aPOETRY / Native American.2bisacsh  aCree poetry.  aCree women's poetry.  aCree women.  aIndigenous literature.  aIndigenous poetics.  aIndigenous poetry.1 aBesner, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaertner, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHenderson, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112350140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771123501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771123501/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles